  "text": "Apache Kafka enforces log retention policy through a coordinated set of components across the broker and storage modules.\n\nConfiguration Definition and Validation:\nServerLogConfigs.java (server-common/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/server/config/) defines the retention configuration constants: LOG_RETENTION_TIME_MILLIS_CONFIG, LOG_RETENTION_TIME_MINUTES_CONFIG, LOG_RETENTION_TIME_HOURS_CONFIG, LOG_RETENTION_BYTES_CONFIG, and LOG_CLEANUP_INTERVAL_MS_CONFIG. LogConfig.java (storage/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/storage/internals/log/) contains the topic-level retention configuration and provides comprehensive validation methods including validateBrokerLogConfigValues, validateRemoteStorageRetentionSize, validateRemoteStorageRetentionTime, and validateRetentionConfigsWhenRemoteCopyDisabled to ensure retention values are valid and properly configured.\n\nBroker-Level Configuration:\nKafkaConfig.scala (core/src/main/scala/kafka/server/) manages broker-level log retention settings through logRetentionTimeMillis and logRetentionBytes properties. It includes validation at line 508 requiring that log.retention.ms must be unlimited (-1) or greater than or equal to 1 millisecond.\n\nLog Manager and Retention Scheduling:\nLogManager.scala (core/src/main/scala/kafka/log/) manages the background retention cleanup process through the cleanupLogs() method, which is scheduled to run periodically at intervals defined by retentionCheckMs. It calls deleteOldSegments() on both regular and future logs to enforce retention policies.\n\nSegment Deletion Enforcement:\nUnifiedLog.java (storage/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/storage/internals/log/) implements the core retention policy enforcement through three key methods:\n\n1. deleteOldSegments(): The main public method (line 1894) that orchestrates deletion of segments breaching any retention policy. It calls deleteLogStartOffsetBreachedSegments(), deleteRetentionSizeBreachedSegments(), and deleteRetentionMsBreachedSegments().\n\n2. deleteRetentionMsBreachedSegments() (line 1908): Enforces time-based retention policy. It retrieves the retention time via UnifiedLog.localRetentionMs() which returns either localRetentionMs or retentionMs depending on whether remote log storage with copy is enabled. It calculates if a segment exceeds retention by comparing current time against the segment's largest timestamp and deletes segments older than the specified retention period.\n\n3. deleteRetentionSizeBreachedSegments() (line 1946): Enforces size-based retention policy. It retrieves the retention size via UnifiedLog.localRetentionSize() and compares the log size against the configured retention size. When log size exceeds the retention limit, it deletes segments until the log size is brought down to acceptable levels.\n\nStatic helper methods localRetentionMs() (line 2646) and localRetentionSize() (line 2650) handle the logic for determining which retention value to use (local vs global) based on remote log storage configuration.\n\nSegment File Deletion:\nLocalLog.java (storage/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/storage/internals/log/) implements the actual deletion of segment files through deleteSegmentFiles() method, which handles both synchronous and asynchronous deletion with configurable delays via config.fileDeleteDelayMs.\n\nDeletion Reason Tracking:\nSegmentDeletionReason.java (storage/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/storage/internals/log/) provides an interface for logging the reason why segments were deleted, allowing tracking of whether deletion was due to time-based or size-based retention breaches."
}

